1
00:00:00,115 --> 00:00:16,690
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambodassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambodassa

2
00:00:17,530 --> 00:00:31,990
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasam Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:32,011 --> 00:00:38,561
So I thought actually this evening for my little Dharma bite, I'd actually do this word Buddha.

4
00:00:40,243 --> 00:00:42,305
And we chanted these...

5
00:00:43,247 --> 00:00:46,514
six, is it six or nine, sorry, nine attributes.

6
00:00:46,753 --> 00:00:50,018
So the first one we say is iti piso bhagava arahant.

7
00:00:50,960 --> 00:00:55,488
This word arahant refers to having completed the path of training.

8
00:00:55,668 --> 00:00:57,832
It's the fourth level of sainthood.

9
00:00:58,893 --> 00:01:03,642
The first one being stream entrance, when a person intuits nibbana.

10
00:01:03,823 --> 00:01:05,204
And then the next two are

11
00:01:05,641 --> 00:01:31,242
developments of that insight see that it's always into the same thing the three characteristics impermanence not self and how we create suffering so this word arahat simply means that he's completed the training to full awakening the next one is this sammasambuddho so fully self-enlightened

12
00:01:32,033 --> 00:01:35,680
So why do we say he was self-enlightened?

13
00:01:35,700 --> 00:01:51,257
Because he went to various teachers and then he practiced mortifications and really the influence we think of the Nagantha, the leader of the Jains, who would have been his elder contemporary.

14
00:01:52,132 --> 00:02:00,885
We say that because remember he comes to a crunch where he leaves his five companions and he sits by the roadside pretty dejected.

15
00:02:01,606 --> 00:02:09,819
And when I contemplate that moment I would have thought it's a pretty heavy moment of anguish because he's left his family.

16
00:02:09,800 --> 00:02:36,280
he's left everything, he's gone out, he's done this training, and it didn't work, and then he's done all this starving himself almost to death, and that didn't work, and there was nothing else on offer, nothing else in the spiritual field on offer, but he was still there with his original problem as to suffering, you know, why was he suffering, and remember in those days it would have been put in terms of continuous rebirth, samsara, you know, the...

17
00:02:36,259 --> 00:02:40,818
There would have been seemingly no end to being reborn in this realm, in that realm.

18
00:02:42,048 --> 00:02:47,475
And it was in that desperation, remember, that he remembers this childhood occasion.

19
00:02:47,856 --> 00:02:58,193
And that's why we say he's self-enlightened, because it was the memory of how he was watching his father doing the ploughing ceremony that gave him the inspiration to sit again.

20
00:02:58,653 --> 00:03:10,451
And of course, what he remembered was that childlike mind, which we develop in our meditation, of just watching, just looking, with that curiosity, that enquiry.

21
00:03:11,443 --> 00:03:15,371
and that's the reason we say he's Sambuddha, he's self-enlightened.

22
00:03:17,313 --> 00:03:33,282
We also say he's Vijaya Charana Sampanno, which means that he is fully developed in both his wisdom and his virtue, and that's something which is important to understand, that those two are concurrent.

23
00:03:33,263 --> 00:03:47,661
You can't grow in wisdom without the growth in virtue, because the defilements we suffer from, the unethical behavior that we commit, is an expression of delusion.

24
00:03:48,181 --> 00:03:49,603
That's what it is.

25
00:03:50,364 --> 00:03:53,889
So as we grow in wisdom, there is a growth in virtue.

26
00:03:54,149 --> 00:03:55,491
You can't have the one without the other.

27
00:03:56,211 --> 00:04:01,497
So I remember, it's not so bad these days, but there was a time you couldn't talk about morality.

28
00:04:01,849 --> 00:04:02,913
People didn't want to know about it.

29
00:04:02,933 --> 00:04:03,896
It was sort of Victorian.

30
00:04:05,643 --> 00:04:06,445
So people would do...

31
00:04:06,807 --> 00:04:12,568
I mean, I know people who used to do six months, you know, head-banging meditation.

32
00:04:13,358 --> 00:04:20,810
and then go out on sex, drugs and rock and roll, and it's like they won't get anywhere.

33
00:04:20,850 --> 00:04:21,872
You can't do that.

34
00:04:21,891 --> 00:04:27,281
At some point there has to be this purification of the heart, this purification of intention.

35
00:04:28,702 --> 00:04:31,247
And it can happen naturally just through the meditation.

36
00:04:31,348 --> 00:04:35,754
It sort of becomes systemic as it drops into the attitude.

37
00:04:35,735 --> 00:04:42,685
or you can develop it as an exercise in itself through right action.

38
00:04:43,166 --> 00:04:54,704
So remember there's an eightfold path, it's not just the onefold path of right understanding, it runs systemically through our intentions, which is based in the heart, our attitudes,

39
00:04:54,685 --> 00:04:59,112
And then through the way we speak, the way we act, and into our livelihood.

40
00:05:00,553 --> 00:05:06,403
So that's why we say he's accomplished both in his wisdom and in his virtue.

41
00:05:06,863 --> 00:05:08,005
The one comes with the other.

42
00:05:10,129 --> 00:05:15,478
Then we say he's sugato, which means he lives a happy life, he's at ease.

43
00:05:17,516 --> 00:05:19,098
He fares well through life.

44
00:05:19,899 --> 00:05:21,201
In other words, he's happy.

45
00:05:22,704 --> 00:05:24,706
He's found the end of suffering.

46
00:05:24,747 --> 00:05:29,012
So when you find the end of suffering, it seems, you're happy, which makes sense, doesn't it?

47
00:05:29,033 --> 00:05:32,817
There was an occasion when somebody complains about the toughness of the training.

48
00:05:33,459 --> 00:05:34,680
And he says, you know, it's hard.

49
00:05:35,180 --> 00:05:39,326
And the Buddha replies, yes, it is, but people attain liberation.

50
00:05:39,346 --> 00:05:40,468
They attain nibbana.

51
00:05:41,408 --> 00:05:43,271
And the guy says, nibbana, so what?

52
00:05:44,112 --> 00:05:48,257
He says, well, when you get to Nibbana, you are contented and really happy.

53
00:05:49,178 --> 00:05:55,387
So the contentment is a mind, is a heart without unskillful desires.

54
00:05:56,329 --> 00:06:06,103
And the happiness is the basic flavor of the mind, which expresses itself in various forms of love, compassion, joy, and so on.

55
00:06:06,124 --> 00:06:06,904
That's where we're heading for.

56
00:06:07,665 --> 00:06:08,247
Have faith.

57
00:06:09,728 --> 00:06:11,911
Then there's the, look how we do.

58
00:06:11,990 --> 00:06:22,666
So he's the knower of the worlds and this really points to, remember, the three insights that he had upon enlightenment.

59
00:06:22,687 --> 00:06:28,115
The first one was all his past lives and how he came to be the enlightenment.

60
00:06:28,134 --> 00:06:35,886
And then he saw that beings moved from one realm to the other according to their moral behavior, which was new for the age.

61
00:06:36,507 --> 00:06:39,110
Most people thought it was just destination.

62
00:06:39,343 --> 00:06:42,427
but our destination is determined by our morality.

63
00:06:43,288 --> 00:06:46,413
And thirdly was that he was free of all defilement.

64
00:06:46,853 --> 00:06:52,721
So in that he's saying he saw how the Lord of Karma works.

65
00:06:53,382 --> 00:06:56,685
And in that case he saw the six worlds.

66
00:06:57,026 --> 00:07:06,499
So there's the hell realms, there's the animal realm, there's the hungry ghost realm, that's a being driven by insatiable desires.

67
00:07:07,423 --> 00:07:12,670
There's the demon world, which are those people driven by hatred and anger and jealousy and all that sort of stuff.

68
00:07:13,891 --> 00:07:15,372
There's the human world, here we are.

69
00:07:16,353 --> 00:07:19,197
And there's the celestial world, which is the happy realm.

70
00:07:19,497 --> 00:07:32,672
And of course, these not only refer to specific realms, which is either provable or not provable, it doesn't matter, but they refer also to our own states of mind.

71
00:07:32,651 --> 00:07:38,180
So if we get drunk, for instance, we've entered into the animal world, the lack of intelligence.

72
00:07:40,343 --> 00:07:47,074
And if you fall into a deep depression or a psychotic episode and things like that, then you're in a hell realm.

73
00:07:47,754 --> 00:07:53,903
Even if it's for a moment where you find yourself in a place like a little panic.

74
00:07:54,444 --> 00:07:57,850
The whole point of those places is that you don't see the escape.

75
00:07:58,370 --> 00:07:59,132
That's hell.

76
00:08:02,386 --> 00:08:05,249
So he's, look how we do, he's the knower of the world.

77
00:08:05,870 --> 00:08:09,394
He's also said to be the Anuttara Purisadhamma Sarati.

78
00:08:09,413 --> 00:08:17,041
So Sarati is a charioteer, so he's a trainer, incomparable trainer of human beings.

79
00:08:17,062 --> 00:08:27,312
And this refers to the fact that he didn't just leave a teaching, he left a methodology which includes the rules of engagement.

80
00:08:27,293 --> 00:08:36,724
So we do the five precepts, you can take on the eight precepts, you can do a ten precepts, and finally you get 227 if you become a monastic.

81
00:08:38,144 --> 00:08:47,395
So all the way he's creating institutions whereby people can actually see the training that they want to get themselves.

82
00:08:47,416 --> 00:08:50,820
And we call them see-carpenter, we don't call them...

83
00:08:50,799 --> 00:09:13,399
commandments sometimes they're called precepts but even that's not quite right they're sikarpada pada means footsteps sikam is training so they are footsteps of training they're the training rules so that's why we say he is the incomparable trainer and leader of human beings

84
00:09:14,830 --> 00:09:27,047
Then we say he is satādeva-manussānāṁ, so sata means a teacher, so he teaches in these two specific realms, the celestial realms, but also to human beings, so he's the actual teacher.

85
00:09:27,427 --> 00:09:28,928
And he takes that role seriously.

86
00:09:28,969 --> 00:09:40,365
There's a point where he may not have taught, but just out of compassion, the desire to pass the good news on to people arose in him.

87
00:09:40,345 --> 00:09:45,500
and the only doubt he had was whether people in fact could receive his message.

88
00:09:46,725 --> 00:09:50,034
And it's put in this mythological sense that the great Brahmā

89
00:09:50,099 --> 00:09:55,164
the great Brahma Sahampati came down and said, there are people with just a little dust in their eyes.

90
00:09:55,946 --> 00:09:58,428
And then he went out and began his teaching.

91
00:09:58,990 --> 00:10:07,480
And one of the little phrases he comes up with, he always says that, whatever a teacher can do out of compassion for his students, I have done for you.

92
00:10:08,120 --> 00:10:10,844
So he's really committed to that whole process.

93
00:10:11,445 --> 00:10:18,232
And all his life, from 35 to 80, he spent just wandering around teaching.

94
00:10:18,836 --> 00:10:46,532
that's his life after that so he's the teacher he's the teacher of gods and men buddho comes from the word budd which just means awakened and I think that's the better word to enlightenment enlightenment gives the impression of something sudden but it's a gradual awakening and here it's almost like an adjective he is the awakened one the buddho

95
00:10:46,511 --> 00:11:13,498
and then finally Bhagavā that's an honorific it means anything from the sublime one to the reverend to the illustrious, the blessed depends how you want to translate it and that's how he's talked of in the scriptures he's referred to as the Bhagavā the blessed one and

96
00:11:15,672 --> 00:11:22,479
And those epithets really, those descriptions of Him, encapsulate this word, Buddha.

97
00:11:24,041 --> 00:11:32,529
So, when we actually take refuge, we are taking refuge in that historical figure, see?

98
00:11:32,950 --> 00:11:35,251
There's a sort of trust, a confidence in that.

99
00:11:36,833 --> 00:11:42,539
But it also, remember, can refer to that within us, which is to be awakened.

100
00:11:45,337 --> 00:12:14,636
of course we don't have to be fully self-enlightened Buddhas there are two other types there's the Pacheco Buddha who is fully self-enlightened but doesn't teach either because he can't it wouldn't be because he won't maybe he just can't and then there is the Svakata Buddha which are those who become Buddhas by simply by following a Buddha so everybody can become the Buddha

101
00:12:17,485 --> 00:12:24,099
And that's about it, my little dharma-bite.

102
00:12:24,119 --> 00:12:26,884
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

103
00:12:27,765 --> 00:12:36,945
May you be fully liberated sooner rather than later.

